Preprocessing

  1. Read the file Toy_Spectronaut_Data.csv into R.
  2. Omit observations with NaN, and save the removed data in the file preprocess_Filtered_Out_NaN.csv in the current working directory.
  3. Filter out proteins with fewer than \(2\) unique peptides, and save the removed data in the file preprocess_Filtered_Out_Unique.csv in the current working directory.
  4. If there are proteins without names, replace blank protein name entries with their protein accessions.
fileName <- "../tests/testData/Toy_Spectronaut_Data.csv"
data <- preprocessing(fileName, filterNaN = TRUE, filterUnique = 2,
                      replaceBlank = TRUE, saveRm = TRUE)

Transformation

Raw intensity measurements, often unsuitable for direct statistical modeling, prompt transformation in most quantitative proteomics workflow. The preferred solution is log-transformation, effectively addressing this issue. The log\(_2\) transformation is commonly employed due to its ability to facilitate the straightforward interpretation of fold changes in protein levels.

dataTran <- transform(data, logFold = 2)

Filtering

For various reasons, such as contamination, lack of informativeness, identification in only a few samples, etc., data will be filtered before conducting differential analysis to exclude certain proteins.

For example, the protein ‘XPO4_HUMAN’ is chosen to be filtered out.

dataFilt <- filterOutIn(dataTran, listName = "XPO4_HUMAN",
                        removeList = TRUE, saveRm = TRUE)

where removeList = TRUE indicates the removal of proteins listed in listName from the dataTran. Please note that if saveRm = TRUE, the excluded data (“XPO4_HUMAN”) will be saved as a .csv file named filtered_out_data.csv in the current working directory.

Imputation

Mass spectrometry-based quantitative proteomics experiments often yield data with missing values, potentially impacting downstream analyses. Various imputation methods have been developed to address this issue. So far, this package provides two imputation methods for use:

  1. “LocalMinVal”: It replaces missing values with the lowest value from the protein by condition combination;

  2. “GlobalMinVal”: It replaces missing values with the lowest value found within the entire dataset.

Additional methods will be added later.

For example, to impute the NA value of dataTran using “LocalMinVal,” set the required percentage of values that must be present in a given protein by condition combination for values to be imputed to \(51\%\).

dataImput <- impute(dataFilt, imputeType = "LocalMinVal",
                    reqPercentPresent = 51, reportImputing = FALSE)

Normalization

Normalization is designed to address systematic biases, enhancing the comparability of samples while preserving the signal. Various normalization approaches have been proposed. So far, this package provides three normalization methods for use:

  1. “quant”: Quantile

  2. “median”: Column-wise Median

  3. “mean”: Column-wise Mean

Quantile normalization is generally recommended.

dataNorm <- normalize(dataImput, normalizeType = "quant")
